Tesla Coil

Cycles are one of the rare market parameters that can be quantitatively measured. But that does not mean it is easy to measure them. In fact, market cycles are so elusive that special techniques must be employed to determine that they even exist in the first place. However, once pinned down, cycles can be an invaluable tool for predicting booms and providing confluence to other indicators such as COG XL and Boom XL. 

So how does one measure a cycle in a sufficiently timely manner to ensure that full advantage can be taken of the knowledge of its existence?  The solution – Tesla Coil.

Background

Named for its lines’ uncanny resemblance to the lightning bolts emitted from a Tesla Coil, this novel indicator solves the challenge of measuring market cycles by simultaneously harnessing the power of three high-end cycle measurement techniques invented by John Ehlers. Two of these techniques – In-Phase and Quadrature Instantaneous Frequency Measurement (I-Q IFM) and Cosine Instantaneous Frequency Measurement (Cosine IFM) – specialize in the precise measurement of longer cycle lengths in both Trending and Ranging market conditions. 

By combining these IFM techniques with a custom, highly optimized Robust Cycle Measurement (RCM) algorithm, averaging the cycles together and graphing the resulting cycle against a scaled-up version of the dominant cycle, we are left with a total of three lines that periodically cross over with each other. Interestingly, these crossovers often coincide with large movements in price action, and thus, in the simplest of use cases, the crossovers themselves can be used as a sort of volatility indicator. 

Tesla Coil has three lines: Blue, Purple, and White. To reduce polarity, each of these lines is mirrored across the x-axis resulting in periodic self-crosses that often have a strong correlation to price movement.

Line Descriptions

Blue Line

The blue line represents the In-Phase & Quadrature IFM. It sums the differential phase angles to obtain an estimate of the dominant cycle. Compared to traditional cycle-measurement approaches, input is filtered prior to performing an Arctangent calculation to reduce noise and provide more reliable output.

White Line

The white line represents the Cosine IFM. This implementation of instantaneous frequency measurement is interesting because it borrows a technique commonly leveraged in the domain of electronic warfare. The data from the input series is decomposed into two signals, which are analogous to the signals detected by radio receivers. Both signals are low pass filtered and their proportion to each other is used to determine differential phase angles. As before, summing these differential phases to 360 degrees provides an estimate of the dominant cycle. This cycle estimate is scaled up by a factor of three to produce the white line.

Purple Line

The purple line is determined by averaging together the other two cycles with a third cycle calculated by using an alternative IFM calculation that has been optimized for shorter periods. This third cycle has an estimated delay of only 8 bars, which helps to offset the bias of the other two methods towards measuring longer cycles in the range of 15-30 bars. The result is a dynamic, multi-cycle average that periodically crosses over with both its mirror as well as the other two lines.

Elliot wave-like patterns tend to generate similar coil patterns. There are several variants, but all are more or less characterized by the following steps in sequence:

  1. a relatively large, expanded blue coil rapidly contracting/converging to a crossover (often has a sideways brachiopod or stingray shape)
  2. a tightly coiled white and purple coil (often overlapping) with concerted crossovers
  3. a rapidly expanding white crossover containing a smaller purple crossover that is also expanding at a slower rate

This brachiopod (left) may be extinct, but its symmetry lives on in Tesla Coil (right).

Tesla Coil ML

Market cycles can be as fickle as they are fleeting, and it is important to remember that even the most seemingly reliable patterns can have exceptions. Even when used alongside other indicators, accurate interpretation of crossovers requires extensive training and practice, as there can often be subtle differences in pattern meanings, especially when switching between multiple securities and time frames. Fortunately, it is precisely this data-driven nature that makes Tesla Coil analysis well suited for a popular type of analysis frequently used in Data Science -- Machine Learning (ML). 

Tesla Coil ML by @jdehorty is a reimplementation of @veryfid’s original Tesla Coil indicator to leverage basic Machine Learning Algorithms to help classify coil crossovers using green and red circles to indicate bullish and bearish bias, respectively. It also includes a dual-purpose MESA Baseline that helps to characterize short-term price fluctuations as well as to provide confluence with the indicator's ML signals.

Red and Green Signals

An ML model (based on Logistic Regression) is dynamically trained and used to generate predictions on price action following coil crossovers. The model is both chart and timeframe specific, making it highly versatile and capable of evolving alongside ever-changing market conditions.

The green and red circles in Tesla Coil ML represent the model’s characterization of a given crossover, with green indicating the cross has a bullish tendency and red indicating the cross has a bearish tendency. You can think of them as the model’s "best guess" on the direction of price action following the crossover based on what it has "learned" from previous crossovers. The "learning" is accomplished using a gradient descent algorithm consisting of the following main steps:

  1. Weight and bias are initialized to zero
  2. Predictions are made using initial weight and bias
  3. Predicted values are compared with actual values through the use of a loss function
  4. Gradient is calculated (i.e. it is determined how the loss function changes with respect to the weight and bias)
  5. Weight and bias are updated

Steps 2-5 occur in a training loop of a predetermined size (i.e. the "Training Iterations" setting). This can be adjusted, but high values may run into memory constraints. The "Learning Rate" setting can be used to fine-tune the training process and is well-optimized by default.

Note: Please do NOT trade off the signals blindly. Always try to use your own intuition for understanding the coils and check for confluence with Boom Hunter XL, and Center of Gravity XL before initiating a trade.

MESA Baseline 

MESA (Maximum Entropy Spectral Analysis) is a cycle measurement method invented by John Ehlers to measure short-term cycles in a market. This makes it an excellent complement to Tesla Coil, which is inherently biased towards longer-term cycles. The MESA Baseline serves a dual purpose:

  1. It indicates the market’s bias at any given point in time with respect to price action, with green indicating a bias towards bullish price movement and red indicating a bias towards bearish price movement
  2. It serves as the baseline/line of symmetry for the reflection of Tesla Coil’s three primary cycles across the baseline to make their respective mirrors. For those that prefer to analyze only crossovers of the upper three coils in relation to the baseline, the mirrors can be disabled via settings.

The colors of the MESA baseline can be used to provide additional confluence for determining cycle transitions and can be used to screen the ML signals. For example, a crossover marked with a green dot that also coincides with a MESA color shift to green will often correspond to a relatively strong bullish price movement. By the same token, a crossover marked with a green dot that coincides with a color shift to red could either be an indicator of a false positive or a sign that the longer and shorter cycles have fallen out of sync with one another, thus leading to a relatively weaker movement in price.
